### Fisher's Iris flower data set

First introduced by Ronald A. Fisher in his 1936 paper [The Use of Multiple Measurements in Taxonomic Problems](http://rcs.chemometrics.ru/Tutorials/classification/Fisher.pdf), this is arguably one of the most well-known data sets in the Statistics community.


The raw data can be obtained from [UCI Machine Learning repository](https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/), or in R, we can simply use the built-in version that comes with a standard R installation.

%md 

### Hierarchical Clustering using R

In this section, we apply hierarchical clustering to the iris data set. Hierarchical clustering is an _unsupervised_ method, but since we know the underlying groups, we can see how well the clustering does.

result.msg:
Hierarchical Clustering using R

In this section, we apply hierarchical clustering to the iris data set. Hierarchical clustering is an unsupervised method, but since we know the underlying groups, we can see how well the clustering does.

paragraphs.text:
%r

# Build Euclidean distance matrix.
distance <- dist(iris[, 1:4], method="euclidean")

# Three clusterings with different linkage function.
fit.s <- hclust(distance, method="single" )
fit.c <- hclust(distance, method="complete")
fit.a <- hclust(distance, method="average")

# Now we cut the average linkage tree @ height 1.82
iris.hc <- cutree(fit.a, h = 1.82)
iris$hc <- iris.hc
%r {"imageWidth": "400px"} plot(fit.s , main = "Single Linkage" , labels=iris$Species )
%r {"imageWidth": "400px"} plot(fit.c , main = "Complete Linkage" , labels=iris$Species)
%r {"imageWidth": "400px"} plot(fit.a , main = "Average Linkage" , labels=iris$Species)

%md 

Now we can check how well the clustering worked by calculating the _adjusted_ Rand index.

result.msg: Now we can check how well the clustering worked by calculating the adjusted Rand index.

paragraphs.text:
%r 
library(mclust)

ri.hc <- adjustedRandIndex(iris$hc, unclass(iris$Species))
ri.hc

%md 

### k-Means Clustering using R

Let's repeat the clustering using _k-Means_. As usual, we'll run the k-Means algorithm over a range of values for _k_ and inspect the total _within cluster sum of squares_ to look for the "statistical elbow".

result.msg:
k-Means Clustering using R

Let's repeat the clustering using k-Means. As usual, we'll run the k-Means algorithm over a range of values for k and inspect the total within cluster sum of squares to look for the “statistical elbow”.

paragraphs.text:
%r
# Compute Within Groups Sum of Squares.
WGSS <- sapply(1:10, function(k) {sum(kmeans(iris[, -5], centers = k)$withinss)})

%r  {"imageWidth": "600px"} plot(1:10, WGSS, type="b", xlab="Number of Clusters",
     ylab="Total Within Groups Sum of Squares")

CL <- 3
points(CL, WGSS[CL], col = "red")

%r

# Now calculate adjusted Rand index for k-Means:

ri.kmeans <- adjustedRandIndex(iris$hc, unclass(iris$Species))
ri.kmeans
